## Zig Idioms in TigerBeetle

### 1. Receiver Naming: The Type Name, Not `self`

TigerBeetle almost never uses `self` as a receiver parameter name. Instead, the receiver is named after the **concrete type** it belongs to, either the full type name or a sensible abbreviation. This is consistent across the entire codebase.

**Pattern:**

```zig
// In src/lsm/tree.zig — receiver is `tree`:
pub fn scope_open(tree: *Tree) void { ... }
pub fn scope_close(tree: *Tree, mode: ScopeCloseMode) void { ... }
pub fn put(tree: *Tree, value: *const Value) void { ... }
pub fn deinit(tree: *Tree, allocator: mem.Allocator) void { ... }

// In src/lsm/table_memory.zig — receiver is `table` or `table_mutable`/`table_immutable`:
pub fn put(table: *TableMemory, value: *const Value) void { ... }
pub fn count(table: *const TableMemory) u32 { ... }
pub fn compact(table_immutable: *TableMemory, table_mutable: *TableMemory, ...) void { ... }

// In src/vsr/repair_budget.zig — receiver is `budget`:
pub fn deinit(budget: *RepairBudgetJournal, gpa: std.mem.Allocator) void { ... }
pub fn decrement(budget: *RepairBudgetJournal, op: u64, ...) ?u8 { ... }
fn assert_invariants(budget: *const RepairBudgetJournal) void { ... }

// In src/vsr/replica.zig — receiver is `self` only when in ReplicaType
pub fn tick(self: *Replica) void { ... }
pub fn deinit(self: *Replica, allocator: Allocator) void { ... }
```

The `Replica` type does use `self`, but that is because the generic `ReplicaType(...)` function returns an anonymous struct whose self-alias is `const Replica = @This();`. The `self` there refers to the concrete `Replica` alias, and most other files use the type's abbreviated name directly.

**The alias pattern for anonymous return types:**

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig
pub fn ReplicaType(...) type {
    return struct {
        const Replica = @This();
        // ...methods use `self: *Replica`
    };
}

// src/vsr/client.zig
pub fn ClientType(...) type {
    return struct {
        const Client = @This();
        // ...methods use `self: *Client`
    };
}

// src/lsm/tree.zig
pub fn TreeType(...) type {
    return struct {
        const Tree = @This();
        // ...methods use `tree: *Tree`
    };
}
```

When a function at the top of a return struct uses `@This()`, it is aliased to a descriptive name and that name is used as the receiver throughout. For non-generic structs, no alias is needed — the receiver is named after the struct directly (e.g., `budget`, `table`).

---

### 2. Enum Switches: Exhaustive `switch` with `unreachable` for Impossible Cases

TigerBeetle never writes redundant `if (x == .foo)` guards after a `switch` has already narrowed the type. When a variant cannot occur legitimately, the arm is `unreachable` — not omitted — so the compiler enforces exhaustiveness:

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig — on_message dispatch is total; impossible variants are explicit
switch (message_any) {
    .ping       => |m| self.on_ping(m),
    .pong       => |m| self.on_pong(m),
    .request    => |m| self.on_request(m),
    .prepare    => |m| self.on_prepare(m),
    // ...
    .pong_client, .eviction => {
        log.warn("{}: on_message: misdirected message ({s})", ...);
        return;
    },
    .reserved       => unreachable,
    .deprecated_12  => unreachable,
    .deprecated_21  => unreachable,
}
```

Notice `.reserved => unreachable` and each deprecated variant get their own arms — no catch-all `else => unreachable`. This ensures that adding a new variant to the `Command` enum creates a compile error, not a silent runtime panic.

**Inline `else` is used when all remaining variants share identical logic**, not to suppress exhaustiveness:

```zig
// src/vsr/client.zig
switch (message.header.into_any()) {
    inline else => |header| {
        log.debug("{}: on_message: {}", .{ self.id, header });
    },
}
```

**For union dispatch on a filtered state,** the code first filters via `if` guard and then `assert`s the remaining cases — it does not repeat the switch predicate redundantly:

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig — on_ping
fn on_ping(self: *Replica, message: *const Message.Ping) void {
    assert(message.header.command == .ping);
    if (self.status != .normal and self.status != .view_change) return;
    // After early return, no further status guard is needed:
    assert(self.status == .normal or self.status == .view_change);
    // ...
}
```

---

### 3. Invariant Checks vs. Input Validation

TigerBeetle draws a hard line between **invariant checks** (should never fail; indicate a bug) and **input validation** (may fail; callers are untrusted).

#### 3a. Internal Invariants → `assert` / `assert_invariants`

`std.debug.assert` is used for any condition that the program logic guarantees. An assert failure = a bug in TigerBeetle itself.

A dedicated private `assert_invariants` function is the standard idiom for validating a struct's consistency pre/post mutation. It is called with `defer` to bracket every public method:

```zig
// src/vsr/repair_budget.zig
fn assert_invariants(budget: *const RepairBudgetJournal) void {
    assert(budget.available <= budget.capacity);
    if (budget.replica_index < budget.replicas_requested_prepares.len) {
        assert(budget.replicas_requested_prepares[budget.replica_index].count() == 0);
    }
    var requested_prepares_count: u32 = 0;
    for (budget.replicas_requested_prepares) |*requested_prepares| {
        requested_prepares_count += @intCast(requested_prepares.count());
    }
    assert(budget.capacity - budget.available == requested_prepares_count);
}

pub fn decrement(budget: *RepairBudgetJournal, ...) ?u8 {
    budget.assert_invariants();   // pre-condition
    defer budget.assert_invariants(); // post-condition
    // ...
}
```

Every mutating method in [`repair_budget.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/repair_budget.zig) brackets with this pattern. [`table_memory.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/table_memory.zig) does the same via field-level asserts at the top of each function.

`Replica.invariants()` is called via `defer` in `tick()` and `on_message()`:

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig
pub fn invariants(self: *const Replica) void {
    assert(self.journal.header_with_op(self.op) != null);
    assert((self.sync_tables == null) == (self.sync_tables_op_range == null));
    assert(self.commit_min <= self.op);
}

pub fn tick(self: *Replica) void {
    // ...
    defer self.invariants();
    // ...
}
fn on_message(self: *Replica, message: *Message) void {
    defer self.invariants();
    // ...
}
```

#### 3b. Pre-conditions at function entry → `assert` cluster

All functions assert their calling contract at the top before doing any work. These are invariants the *caller* must satisfy:

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig
fn on_request(self: *Replica, message: *Message.Request) void {
    if (self.ignore_request_message(message)) return;

    assert(self.status == .normal);
    assert(self.primary());
    assert(self.syncing == .idle);
    assert(self.commit_min == self.commit_max);
    assert(message.header.command == .request);
    assert(message.header.operation != .reserved);
    // ...
}
```

The `ignore_request_message` early-return gate (see §4 below) does all the *input validation*. Everything after `if (self.ignore_...) return;` can be asserted as invariants.

#### 3c. External / untrusted input → `if ... return` or `log.warn` + return

For messages from the network (or from clients), validation is done with early returns, not asserts:

```zig
// src/vsr/client.zig
pub fn on_message(self: *Client, message: *Message) void {
    if (message.header.invalid()) |reason| {
        log.debug("{}: on_message: invalid ({s})", .{ self.id, reason });
        return;  // ← NOT assert(message.header.invalid() == null)
    }
    if (message.header.cluster != self.cluster) {
        log.warn("{}: on_message: wrong cluster ...", ...);
        return;
    }
    // ...
}
```

The distinction is clear: untrusted bytes from the network get `if ... return`; internal state that must hold gets `assert`.

#### 3d. `maybe()` — the dual of `assert`

TigerBeetle adds a custom [`stdx.maybe`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/stdx.zig#L328-L335) function:

```zig
/// `maybe` is the dual of `assert`: it signals that condition is sometimes true
///  and sometimes false.
///
/// Currently we use it for documentation, but maybe one day we plug it into
/// coverage.
pub fn maybe(ok: bool) void {
    assert(ok or !ok);
}
```

It is used throughout to annotate conditions that *can* be either true or false at a given point — explicitly documenting that the author considered the case and it is not an invariant. Examples from [`replica.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/replica.zig):

```zig
maybe(self.status == .normal);
maybe(self.status == .view_change);
maybe(self.status == .recovering_head);
if (self.status == .recovering) assert(self.solo());
```

This is a "reachability annotation" pattern: `assert` = always true, `maybe` = can be either, `unreachable` = never reachable. Together they make every branch explicitly documented.

---

### 4. `ignore_*` Guard Functions for State-Machine Pre-flight

Message handlers that only apply to specific replica states use a dedicated private `ignore_*` function to consolidate all the multi-status guard logic. This keeps the handler body clean for asserting invariants, avoids repeating complex status checks:

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig
fn on_request(self: *Replica, message: *Message.Request) void {
    if (self.ignore_request_message(message)) return;

    // Everything after this is asserted, not guarded:
    assert(self.status == .normal);
    assert(self.primary());
    // ...
}

fn on_ping_client(self: *Replica, message: *const Message.PingClient) void {
    if (self.ignore_ping_client(message)) return;
    // ...
}
```

The `ignore_*` function logs the reason for ignoring and returns `true`, allowing the handler to be free of conditional noise.

---

### 5. Comptime-asserted Field Invariants in Struct Doc-Comments

Invariants that are not easily runtime-checkable are documented inline in field comments with a formal notation:

```zig
// src/vsr/replica.zig (field documentation)
/// Runtime upper-bound size of a `operation=request` message.
/// Does not change after initialization.
/// Invariants:
/// - request_size_limit > @sizeOf(Header)
/// - request_size_limit ≤ message_size_max
request_size_limit: u32,

/// Invariant: node_count = replica_count + standby_count
node_count: u8,

/// Invariants:
/// - (sync_view ≠ null) ⇔ (syncing ∈ {.canceling_commit, .canceling_checkpoint})
sync_view: ?*Message.View = null,
```

These document structural invariants that `assert_invariants` or `tick`'s `defer` checks enforce at runtime.

